benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/healthcheck - Put the host out of rotation

covered: Valid Deletion: TC01 and TC12 cover successful removal of host from rotation and regression case confirms host is marked out of rotation.
Concurrency: TC11 tests concurrent requests and expected outcomes.
Authorization: TC02 and TC03 validate behavior with missing/invalid authentication.

Error Handling: TC04 (already out of rotation -> 409), TC05 (service down -> 503), TC06 (system error -> 500), TC07 (invalid HTTP method -> 405), TC09 (malicious body -> 400), TC13 (insecure headers -> 400/401), TC14 (edge case no hosts -> 409).
Additional Scenarios: TC08 (extra parameters), TC10 (performance under normal load), TC11 (performance under concurrency), TC12 (regression), TC14 (edge case no hosts)
gaps: Non-Existent Resource: No explicit 404 handling for deleting when no resource or host entry exists beyond the edge case of “no hosts in rotation” which returns 409.
Unauthorized Elevation/403: No scenario specifically verifying 403 Forbidden for insufficient privileges.
Rate Limiting: No tests for throttling or rate limiting.
Caching Behavior: No tests for caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control).
Pagination: Not applicable for DELETE, but guideline mentions for GET/pagination in data-heavy endpoints; no coverage needed here.
recommendations: Add a 404 Not Found scenario for DELETE /1.0/kb/admin/healthcheck when the resource/host does not exist beyond the “no hosts in rotation” edge case, to confirm proper non-existent resource handling.
Include a 403 Forbidden scenario to verify proper authorization levels beyond basic 401/invalid token cases.
Introduce rate-limiting/throttling tests to ensure the API handles bursty DELETE requests gracefully.
Add tests to verify caching headers presence/absence where applicable (ETag, Cache-Control) for DELETE responses, if caching is expected.
Consider clarifying the edge case coverage by distinguishing between “no hosts available” vs. “host not found” to ensure consistent error codes across similar scenarios.
